FIXC_ECOLI	P68644	Localization: peripheral inner membrane protein/the protein has hydrophobic patches all over its sequence/Could be part of an electron transfer system required for anaerobic carnitine reduction so this is consistent with a membrane association. ; strong prediction on both Phobius and TmHMM for an aminoterminal weakly hydrophobic region ; Other studies propose that this sequence may be an aminoterminal signal peptide without evidence for cleavage (http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jobm.3620350404/pdf). The fixABCX Genes in Rhodospirillum rubrum Encode a Putative Membrane Complex Participating in Electron Transfer to Nitrogenase where FixA and B are soluble proteins but the RrFixC was expressed in E.coli and localized at the membrane fraction and is not carbonate extracted suggesting that it is an integral membrane protein (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC374401/). From another study in Rhizobia, primary sequence homology, the FixC family is a highly conserved flavoprotein distantly related to the mitochondrial ETF-QO (a peripheral, membrane-associated ETF : ubiquinone oxidoreductase) yet lacking both hydrophobic and amphipathic transmembrane {alpha}-helices (http://mic.sgmjournals.org/cgi/content/full/150/1/117). Thus, the authors state that FixC family is unlikely to be stably membrane-associated. FTSA_ECOLI	P0ABH0	Localization: <putative> peripheral inner membrane protein Notes: has a conserved C-terminal membrane targeting sequence (MTS) with extremely weak TmHMM and Phobius predictions. Deletion or point mutations in the MTS, inactivate FtsA function and inhibit cell division. Because FtsA binds to the tubulin-like FtsZ protein that forms the Z ring, it is thought that the MTS of FtsA is required, along with the transmembrane protein ZipA, to assemble the Z ring and anchor it to the cytoplasmic membrane. FtsA function in cell division depends on additive effects of membrane binding and self-interaction, and that the specific requirement of an amphipathic helix for tethering FtsA to the membrane can be bypassed. No obious bochemical reason that the enzyme should be secreted. Signal peptide like sequence could act as peripheral membrane association element ; Lipopolysaccharide (LPS) is an amphiphilic molecule composed of a hydrophilic heteropolysaccharide and the membrane-embedded lipid A. The innermost 8-carbon sugar 3-deoxy-D-manno-oct-2-ulosonic acid (KDO) is the only conserved structural element found in all LPS, linking the lipid A to the carbohydrate domain of the molecule. The KDO 8-phosphate phosphatase (KdsC) is one of the enzymes of the KDO biosynthesis pathway and is responsible for cleavage of the phosphate group from KDO 8-phosphate to yield KDO. It is not known if association is direct. The protein has weak hydrophobic patches and three regions with weak predictions from Phobius for membrane interaction. Membrane association may be via binding to RNAaseE with which PNPase interacts as part of the multienzyme complex known as the RNA degradosome. RNAseE has been shown to bind to membranes (Khemici et al., 2008). . The interac tion of RNase E with PNPase, an , brings together two enzymes important in the degradation of mRNA. RPOE_ECOLI	P0AGB6	Localization: Peripheral IM Cytoplasmic side Notes: SigmaE controls the σE-dependent extracytoplasmic stress response. σE is held at the membrane by the antisigma factor RseA. RseB binds to the periplasmic domain of RseA and protects RseA from proteolysis. Unfolded OMPs activate the protease DegS, which cleaves the periplasmic domain of RseA. The partially degraded RseA is now a substrate for RseP. RseP cleaves RseA further, releasing the cytoplasmic domain of RseA bound to σE. This remaining domain of RseA is degraded by ClpXP thereby freeing σE to interact with RNA polymerase and direct transcription of its regulon ; Part of the ECF family of sigma factors; The rpoE gene is part of a multicistronic operon that includes the rseA, rseB and rseC genes. RseA is an inner membrane protein while RseB is a periplasmic protein (De Las Penas et al., 1997 and Missiakas et al., 1997). The periplasmic domain of RseA interacts with RseB while its cytoplasmic domain interacts with RpoE, thereby sequestering RpoE away from the transcription complex. Presence of misfolded proteins in the periplasm results in the sequestration of RseB away from the ternary inhibitory complex, thus alleviating the inhibition of RseA on RpoE ( Collinet et al., 2000). RseB, therefore acts as the sensor protein. Refs: (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18253509) ; Anna Lopez 2005 (http://www.mcponline.org/content/4/8/1205.abstract) ; Bashyam et al., 2004 review (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15374527)	RNA polymerase sigma-E factor (Sigma-24)	F1		Cytoplasmic >EXP<			P0AGB6		Common Core	0	0	0	0		CYT 		34	0.052	0	0.02	0.00		0	MSEQLTDQVLVERVQKGDQKAFNLLVVRYQHKVASLVSRYVPSGDVPDVVQEAFIKAYRALDSFRGDSAFYTWLYRIAVNTAKNYLVAQGRRPPSSDVDAIEAENFESGGALKEISNPENLMLSEELRQIVFRTIESLPEDLRMAITLRELDGLSYEEIAAIMDCPVGTVRSRIFRAREAIDNKVQPLIRR

UBIH_ECOLI	P25534	Localization: peripheral inner membrane protein The biosynthesis of UQ is studied in great detail in bacteria and yeast but only to a limited extent in animal tissues (ref.1, 3, 4 ). The UQ biosynthetic enzymes may constitute a complex that is tightly bound to the membrane. In the biosynthetic pathway the “ nucleus” of UQ is derived from the shikimate pathway via chorismate in bacteria or tyrosine in higher eukaryotes. Our subsytem analysis suggests that many bacteria lacking UbiC may also depend on an alternative (and yet unknown) source of 4-hydroxybenzoate. The prenyl side chain of UQ is derived from prenyl diphosphate and methyl groups are derived from S-adenosylmethionine. USPA_ECOLI	P0AED0	Localization: Peripheral IM Cytoplasmic side Notes: The Usp superfamily encompasses an ancient and conserved group of proteins that are found in bacteria, archaea,fungi, flies and plants. Usually each organism has several copies of Usp genes. Escherichia coli contains six Uspproteins, which can be divided into two subfamilies on the basis of sequence similarity.24 Three of these proteins belong to the UspA subfamily (UspA, UspC, and UspD), and two to the UspFG subfamily (UspF and UspG). Another homologue is YbdQ. UspC binds to the membrane-integrated sensor kinase KdpD involved in K+ ion sensing. The same could be true for the other Usp proteins but we could not find direct evidence in the literature. YRAP_ECOLI	P64596	Localization: Inner membrane lipoprotein or peripheral inner membrane protein facing the periplasm Notes: Strong LipoP and SP predictions ; Contains 2 BON domains. IPR007055 (http://www.ebi.ac.uk/interpro/DisplayIproEntry?ac=IPR007055) These are found in a family of osmotic shock protection proteins (e.g. P27291). It is also found in some Secretins and a group of potential haemolysins. Its likely function is attachment to phospholipid membranes ; Is homologous to the OsmY_Ecoli protein. The BON domain is typically ~60 residues long and has an alpha/beta predicted fold. There is a conserved glycine residue and several hydrophobic regions. This pattern of conservation is more suggestive of a binding or structural function rather than a catalytic function. Most proteobacteria seem to possess one or two BON-containing proteins, typically of the OsmY-type proteins; outside of this group the distribution is more disparate ; OsmY protein is a 20 kDa outer membrane or periplasmic protein that is expressed in response to a variety of stress conditions, in particular, helping to provide protection against osmotic shock. One hypothesis is that OsmY prevents shrinkage of the cytoplasmic compartment by contacting the phospholipid interfaces surrounding the periplasmic space. The domain architecture of two BON domains alone suggests that these domains contact the surfaces of phospholipids, with each domain contacting a membrane Refs: Yeats 2003 (www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12878000)	Uncharacterized protein yraP	I	Periplasm. 	-	SEC	LOL	P64596			23	0.999	23	0.655	18	SpII 	13.040	34	0.166	1	21.94	21.94	21	0	MKALSPIAVLISALLLQGCVAAAVVGTAAVGTKAATDPRSVGTQVDDGTLEVRVNSALSKDEQIKKEARINVTAYQGKVLLVGQSPNAELSARAKQIAMGVDGANEVYNEIRQGQPIGLGEASNDTWITTKVRSQLLTSDLVKSSNVKVTTENGEVFLMGLVTEREAKAAADIASRVSGVKRVTTAFTFIK
